 The correct approach to this question is to notice that the summation of the last and first terms will have an $n$ in the denominator. By performing the summation with a general form $let \ S = \sum_{n = 1}^{2009} \frac {2} {n(n+2)}$, we can break $2$ into $\frac {A} {n} + \ \frac {B} {n+2}$. It turns out that there exists zero, so we have the solution: $ let \ S = \sum_{n = 1}^{2009} \frac {2} {n(n+2)} = \sum_{n = 1}^{2009} \frac {1} {n} + \ \frac {-1} {n+2}$</think>
\begin{align*} \sum_{n = 1}^{2009} \frac {2} {n(n+2)} & = \sum_{n = 1}^{2009} \bigg({ \frac{n-2+2-1} {n(n+2)} = \ \frac {1} {n} + \frac {-1} {n+2} } \bigg) \\ \\ & \sum_{n = 1}^{2009} \frac {2} {n(n+2)} = \frac {1} {1} + \frac {1} {2} -  \frac {1} {2010} - \frac {1} {2011} \\ \\ & \sum_{n = 1}^{2009} \frac {2} {n(n+2)} = 1.5 - (0.000495 - 0.000495) \\ \\& \sum_{n = 1}^{2009} \frac {2} {n(n+2)} =1.5 \\ \\ \end{align*}
Thus, the answer is $\boxed{1.500}$.

