Now, $x,y\in[0,\pi]$, so in particular, $x,y\in[0,\pi]\cup\{-\pi\}$. Hence, $\pi\not\in(-\pi,x+y\text{ or }\pi,y)$. Thus, evaluating $\sin(x+y)$ and $\sin(x)+\sin y$ by considering which of $x+y$ and $\pi(x+y)$ lies in $[0,\pi]$ is enough to determine which of $\sin(x+y)$ and $\sin(x)+\sin(y$) is larger (and why). If $2x+y\in[0,\pi]$, then by the addition formula for cosine, \begin{align*}\sin(x+y)-\sin(x)-\sin(y)&=\sin(x)\cos(y)+\cos(x)\sin(y)\\&-\sin(x)-\sin(y)\\&=\sin(x)(\cos(y)-1)+\sin(y)\cos(x)-\cos(x)+1\\&=\sin(x)\left(-\frac{1-\cos^2(y)}{\cos(y)}\right)-\left(1+\cos(x)\right)(1-\cos(x))\\&=-\frac{\sin(x)(1-\cos^2y)}{\cos(y)}-(1-\cos^2(x))\geq 0,\end{align*}because each of the three quantities on the far right is at most $0$. Therefore, we conclude $\sin(x+y)\leq \sin(x)+\sin(y)$ in this case. On the other hand, if $x+2y\in[0,\pi]$, then with the first fact and $[\ast]:x+2y=x+(x+y)+y$, \begin{align*}\sin(x)+\sin(y)+\sin(x+y)&=2\sin\left(\frac{x+x+y}{2}\right)\cos\left(\frac{x+y}{2}\right)+\sin(x+y)\\&=\sin(x)\cos\left(\frac{x+y}{2}\right)+\cos(x)\sin\left(\frac{x+y}{2}\right)+\sin(x+y)\\&\leq\left|\frac{x}{2}\right|+\left|\frac{x+y}{2}\right|+\left|\frac{2\pi-x-y}{2}\right|+\left(\frac{2\pi-x-y}{2}\right)\\&=\frac{x}{2}+\frac{x+y}{2}+\frac{2\pi-x-y}{2}+\pi\\&=\frac{3\pi}{2}\leq \pi,\end{align*}because $x,2\pi-x\leq \pi$, $y,2\pi-y\leq\pi$, and $2\pi-x-y\leq \pi$ by the fact that $x,y\in [0,\pi]$. Therefore, we conclude $\sin(x)+\sin(y)+\sin(x+y)\leq\pi$. Combining this with the upper bound on $\sin(x+y)$, we see that the desired inequality holds in this case as well.
